  <div class="lesson open" id="l7">
    <div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson('l7')">
      <span class="lesson-num">LESSON 7 · Week 5</span>
      <span class="lesson-title">Recursion, For Loop, Variable Scope, Break / Continue</span>
      <span class="lesson-meta">4 core concepts</span>
      <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
    </div>
    <div class="lesson-body">

      <div class="framework-banner">
        <div class="framework-icon">🏗️</div>
        <div>
          <h3>WHY THIS LESSON EXISTS</h3>
          <p>This lesson is all about making programs repeat work. A for loop lets you process data in bulk; recursion gives you a completely different problem-solving pattern; variable scope tells you when a variable exists and when it disappears. These three ideas are the foundation of every useful program you'll write.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- RECURSION -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-recursion">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Recursion
          <span class="tag tag-logic">🧠 Understand the logic</span>
          <span class="tag tag-key">⭐ Must know</span>
        </div>

        <p>Recursion means a function calls itself. Every recursive function needs exactly two things — miss either one and it breaks:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Base case</strong> — tells the function when to stop. Without this, it loops forever and crashes.</li>
          <li><strong>Recursive step</strong> — calls itself, but each time it must move one step closer to the base case.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">countdown</span>(n):
    <span class="kw">if</span> n &lt;= <span class="num">0</span>:                    <span class="cm"># ← Base case — stop here!</span>
        <span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="str">'Blastoff!'</span>)
    <span class="kw">else</span>:
        <span class="fn">print</span>(n)
        <span class="fn">countdown</span>(n - <span class="num">1</span>)        <span class="cm"># ← Recursive step — n shrinks toward 0</span></div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          Imagine counting a stack of plates. You pick up the top one, count "1," then hand the rest to the person next to you — who does exactly the same thing. The last person finds no plates left (base case), says "0," and the answer gets passed back up the chain. That's recursion.
        </div>

        <p><strong>Recursion vs. a regular loop — when to use which?</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Deep recursion, care about memory or speed → use a loop (while or for)</li>
          <li>Not performance-sensitive, but want cleaner code → recursion is fine</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- FOR LOOP -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-forloop">
        <div class="topic-title">
          For Loop syntax + range()
          <span class="tag tag-memory">📝 Memorize</span>
          <span class="tag tag-key">⭐ Must know</span>
        </div>

        <p>Basic for loop grammar:</p>
        <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">for</span> variable <span class="kw">in</span> sequence:    <span class="cm"># sequence = any iterable (list, string, range…)</span>
    instructions               <span class="cm"># indented — runs once per element</span></div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          Think of a teacher calling roll. She holds a list (sequence), reads out one name at a time (variable gets assigned that name), that student stands up and answers (loop body runs), then she moves to the next name.
        </div>

        <p style="margin-top:0.75rem"><strong>Three forms of range() — you need to know all three cold:</strong></p>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <tr><th>Syntax</th><th>Numbers generated</th><th>How to remember it</th></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>range(5)</kbd></td><td>0, 1, 2, 3, 4</td><td>0 up to (but not including) end</td></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>range(3, 7)</kbd></td><td>3, 4, 5, 6</td><td>start up to (but not including) end</td></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>range(10, 2, -2)</kbd></td><td>10, 8, 6, 4</td><td>step can be negative — counts backward</td></tr>
        </table>

        <div class="trap">
          <span class="trap-label">⚠️ EXTREMELY COMMON MISTAKE</span>
          range() <strong>never includes the right endpoint</strong>. This is called a half-open interval, written [start, end). Easy to forget — and when you do, you're off by one element.
        </div>

        <p style="margin-top:0.75rem"><strong>For loop or while loop?</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>For</strong> — you know how many times to iterate, or you're processing every element in a sequence.</li>
          <li><strong>While</strong> — you don't know how many iterations you need; you run until some condition is met (e.g., keep prompting the user until they enter valid input).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- VARIABLE SCOPE -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-scope">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Variable Scope
          <span class="tag tag-logic">🧠 Understand the logic</span>
        </div>

        <p>In Python, the smallest "local" scope is the <strong>function body</strong> — not an if/for/while block. This means:</p>
        <p>A variable defined inside an if or for block is accessible outside it — <em>as long as that branch actually ran</em>. If the branch never executed, the variable doesn't exist yet, and accessing it raises a <kbd>NameError</kbd>.</p>

        <div class="code-block">
x = <span class="num">5</span>
<span class="kw">if</span> x > <span class="num">0</span>:
    y = x
<span class="fn">print</span>(y)    <span class="cm"># ✅ Fine — the if ran, so y exists. Prints 5.</span>

<span class="cm"># ─────────────────────────────────────</span>

x = <span class="num">5</span>
<span class="kw">if</span> x > <span class="num">0</span>:
    y = x
<span class="kw">else</span>:
    z = -x    <span class="cm"># x=5 > 0, so the else branch never ran</span>
<span class="fn">print</span>(z)    <span class="cm"># ❌ NameError — z was never created</span></div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          Only if you actually open a package does its contents end up in your hands. If that if/else branch never ran, the variable was never placed in memory — so of course you can't reach it.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- BREAK / CONTINUE -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-breakcontinue">
        <div class="topic-title">
          break and continue
          <span class="tag tag-memory">📝 Know the difference</span>
        </div>

        <table class="compare-table">
          <tr><th>Keyword</th><th>What it does</th><th>Analogy</th></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>break</kbd></td><td>Exit the entire loop immediately — all remaining iterations are cancelled</td><td>Skipping class entirely — you walk out the door</td></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>continue</kbd></td><td>Skip the rest of this iteration and jump straight to the next one</td><td>Sleeping through one class — you're still in the room, but this one doesn't count</td></tr>
        </table>

        <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">11</span>):
    <span class="kw">if</span> i == <span class="num">5</span>:
        <span class="kw">break</span>
    <span class="fn">print</span>(i, end=<span class="str">" "</span>)
<span class="cm"># Output: 1 2 3 4  ← hits 5 and bails completely</span>

<span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">11</span>):
    <span class="kw">if</span> i == <span class="num">5</span>:
        <span class="kw">continue</span>
    <span class="fn">print</span>(i, end=<span class="str">" "</span>)
<span class="cm"># Output: 1 2 3 4 6 7 8 9 10  ← skips 5, everything else prints</span></div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

