      <!-- MODULES -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-modules">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Modules — four ways to import
          <span class="tag tag-memory">📝 Memorize the syntax</span>
        </div>

        <p>A module is a .py file full of reusable code. Import it and use whatever's inside. There are four import styles, each with a different trade-off:</p>

        <table class="compare-table">
          <tr><th>Syntax</th><th>How to call it</th><th>Best when…</th></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>import math</kbd></td><td><kbd>math.sqrt(16)</kbd></td><td>Safest — no risk of name collisions</td></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>from math import sqrt</kbd></td><td><kbd>sqrt(16)</kbd></td><td>You only need a few functions; keeps code short</td></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>from math import *</kbd></td><td><kbd>sqrt(16)</kbd></td><td>Use with caution — may overwrite your own variable names</td></tr>
          <tr><td><kbd>import math as m</kbd></td><td><kbd>m.sqrt(16)</kbd></td><td>Module name is long; alias saves typing</td></tr>
        </table>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          <kbd>import math</kbd> = borrowing an entire textbook — you have to look everything up by chapter (math.xxx). <kbd>from math import sqrt</kbd> = photocopying just the page you need and clipping it into your notebook. <kbd>from math import *</kbd> = copying the whole book into your notes — fine until you already have your own note called "sqrt" and everything gets confused.
        </div>

        <p style="margin-top:0.75rem"><strong>__name__ and __main__</strong> <span class="tag tag-logic" style="vertical-align:middle">🧠 Logic</span></p>
        <p>When a .py file is <strong>run directly</strong>, Python automatically sets <kbd>__name__</kbd> to <kbd>"__main__"</kbd>. When it's imported by another file, <kbd>__name__</kbd> becomes the module's filename instead.</p>
        <p>The idiom <kbd>if __name__ == "__main__":</kbd> at the bottom of a file means: only run this code when executed directly, not when imported. This lets a file serve as both a reusable library and a standalone script.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- RANDOM -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-random">
        <div class="topic-title">
          The random module
          <span class="tag tag-memory">📝 Memorize the API names</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
<span class="kw">import</span> random

random.<span class="fn">random</span>()              <span class="cm"># Random float in [0.0, 1.0) — 1.0 is never returned</span>
random.<span class="fn">randint</span>(<span class="num">2</span>, <span class="num">5</span>)        <span class="cm"># Random int, 2 to 5 inclusive (both endpoints included!)</span>
random.<span class="fn">seed</span>(<span class="num">123</span>)             <span class="cm"># Fix the seed so results are reproducible</span></div>

        <div class="trap">
          <span class="trap-label">⚠️ EASY CONFUSION</span>
          <kbd>randint(2, 5)</kbd> <strong>includes both endpoints</strong> — 2 and 5 are both possible. But <kbd>range(2, 5)</kbd> excludes 5. Same-looking syntax, opposite endpoint rules. Don't mix them up.
        </div>

        <p><strong>Why use random.seed()?</strong> With the same seed, every run of your program produces the same "random" sequence. Invaluable when testing — you can reproduce exact results.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- STRINGS -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-strings">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Strings — indexing, slicing, methods
          <span class="tag tag-memory">📝 Memorize</span>
          <span class="tag tag-key">⭐ Must know</span>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Indexing</strong> — first character is [0], last is [-1]:</p>
        <div class="code-block">
fruit = <span class="str">'banana'</span>
fruit[<span class="num">0</span>]     <span class="cm"># 'b'</span>
fruit[-<span class="num">1</span>]    <span class="cm"># 'a' — negative index counts from the end</span>
fruit[<span class="num">1000</span>]  <span class="cm"># ❌ IndexError — out of range</span></div>

        <p style="margin-top:0.75rem"><strong>Slicing</strong> — <kbd>s[start : end : step]</kbd>, one of the most useful tricks in Python:</p>
        <div class="code-block">
s = <span class="str">'Hello world'</span>
s[<span class="num">0</span>:<span class="num">5</span>]       <span class="cm"># 'Hello'  — index 0 to 4, end is excluded</span>
s[<span class="num">6</span>:]        <span class="cm"># 'world'  — from index 6 to the end</span>
s[<span class="num">0</span>:<span class="num">5</span>:<span class="num">2</span>]     <span class="cm"># 'Hlo'    — every other character</span>
s[::<span class="num">-1</span>]      <span class="cm"># 'dlrow olleH' — reverses the string (classic trick)</span></div>

        <p style="margin-top:0.75rem"><strong>Commonly used string methods:</strong></p>
        <div class="concept-grid">
          <div class="concept-card"><strong>s.lower() / s.upper()</strong><span>Convert to all lowercase / uppercase — returns a new string</span></div>
          <div class="concept-card"><strong>s.replace(old, new)</strong><span>Replace every occurrence of old with new</span></div>
          <div class="concept-card"><strong>s.count(c)</strong><span>Count how many times c appears</span></div>
          <div class="concept-card"><strong>s.find(c)</strong><span>Index of first occurrence; returns -1 if not found</span></div>
        </div>

        <div class="trap">
          <span class="trap-label">⚠️ THE MOST IMPORTANT STRING RULE</span>
          Strings are <strong>immutable</strong> — once created, they cannot be changed. Every method returns a <strong>new string</strong>; the original is untouched. You cannot do <kbd>s[0] = 'X'</kbd> — Python will throw a <kbd>TypeError</kbd> immediately.
        </div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          A string is like text carved into stone. You can't go back and chisel out one letter — you have to carve a whole new stone (create a new string).
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

