  <div class="lesson" id="l9">
    <div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson('l9')">
      <span class="lesson-num">LESSON 9 · Week 7</span>
      <span class="lesson-title">Three Ways to Traverse a String</span>
      <span class="lesson-meta">2 core concepts</span>
      <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
    </div>
    <div class="lesson-body">

      <div class="framework-banner">
        <div class="framework-icon">🔍</div>
        <div>
          <h3>WHY THIS LESSON EXISTS</h3>
          <p>Traversing (iterating through) a string one character at a time is the foundation of all text processing. Each of the three approaches has a different use case — knowing when to reach for each one will make your code cleaner and reduce bugs significantly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="topic" id="anchor-traverse">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Three traversal methods compared
          <span class="tag tag-logic">🧠 Understand the difference</span>
          <span class="tag tag-key">⭐ Must know</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
text = <span class="str">'orange'</span>

<span class="cm"># Method 1: while + manual index (most flexible, most error-prone)</span>
index = <span class="num">0</span>
<span class="kw">while</span> index &lt; <span class="fn">len</span>(text):
    <span class="fn">print</span>(text[index])
    index += <span class="num">1</span>

<span class="cm"># Method 2: for + range (lets you access both index and character)</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(<span class="fn">len</span>(text)):
    <span class="fn">print</span>(text[i])

<span class="cm"># Method 3: for directly over the string (cleanest, no index available)</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> char <span class="kw">in</span> text:
    <span class="fn">print</span>(char)</div>

        <table class="compare-table">
          <tr><th>Method</th><th>Index available?</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
          <tr><td>while + manual index</td><td>✅ Yes</td><td>When you need to skip around (e.g., jump two positions at a time)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>for + range</td><td>✅ Yes</td><td>When you need to know the position of the current character</td></tr>
          <tr><td>for directly over string</td><td>❌ No</td><td>When you only care about the character itself — the most Pythonic way</td></tr>
        </table>

        <div class="trap">
          <span class="trap-label">⚠️ OFF-BY-ONE ERROR — the most common bug here</span>
          Writing <kbd>range(len(text) + 1)</kbd> causes an IndexError. Valid indices are 0 to len−1. Adding an extra +1 pushes you one past the end — the program crashes immediately.
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
