        <div>
          <h3>WHY THIS LESSON EXISTS</h3>
          <p>Real-world data is often two-dimensional — spreadsheets, matrices, pixel grids. Nested lists + nested loops are the standard pattern for handling it. split() and join() are essential text-processing tools; you'll use them in almost every program that reads or writes text.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- NESTED LOOPS -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-nestedloops">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Nested loops
          <span class="tag tag-logic">🧠 Understand execution order</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
<span class="cm"># Multiplication table: outer loop = rows, inner loop = columns</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">6</span>):           <span class="cm"># outer advances once…</span>
    <span class="kw">for</span> j <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">range</span>(<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">13</span>):       <span class="cm"># …inner completes a full cycle</span>
        <span class="fn">print</span>(i * j, end=<span class="str">' '</span>)
    <span class="fn">print</span>()                        <span class="cm"># newline after each outer iteration</span></div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          Nested loops are like searching a parking garage for a free spot. The outer loop is "which floor," the inner loop is "check every spot on this floor." The outer moves one step, the inner runs a full lap.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- NESTED LISTS -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-nestedlists">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Nested lists
          <span class="tag tag-logic">🧠 Understand indexing</span>
          <span class="tag tag-key">⭐ Must know</span>
        </div>

        <p>A nested list is a list of lists — the standard way to represent 2D data like a matrix or table.</p>

        <div class="code-block">
matrix = [[<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">2</span>, <span class="num">3</span>],
          [<span class="num">4</span>, <span class="num">5</span>, <span class="num">6</span>],
          [<span class="num">7</span>, <span class="num">8</span>, <span class="num">9</span>]]

matrix[<span class="num">1</span>]       <span class="cm"># [4, 5, 6]  — entire second row</span>
matrix[<span class="num">1</span>][<span class="num">2</span>]    <span class="cm"># 6          — second row, third column</span>
<span class="cm"># Rule: matrix[row][column] — always row first, then column</span></div>
      </div>

      <!-- SPLIT / JOIN -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-splitjoin">
        <div class="topic-title">
          String ↔ List conversion: split() and join()
          <span class="tag tag-memory">📝 Memorize the syntax</span>
          <span class="tag tag-key">⭐ Must know</span>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
<span class="cm"># String → List: use split()</span>
<span class="str">"Hello world"</span>.<span class="fn">split</span>()         <span class="cm"># ['Hello', 'world']  — splits on whitespace by default</span>
<span class="str">"a-b-c"</span>.<span class="fn">split</span>(<span class="str">'-'</span>)            <span class="cm"># ['a', 'b', 'c']     — splits on the delimiter '-'</span>
<span class="fn">list</span>(<span class="str">"Hi"</span>)                      <span class="cm"># ['H', 'i']          — splits into individual characters</span>

<span class="cm"># List → String: use join()</span>
<span class="str">' '</span>.<span class="fn">join</span>([<span class="str">'Hello'</span>, <span class="str">'world'</span>])  <span class="cm"># 'Hello world'</span>
<span class="str">','</span>.<span class="fn">join</span>([<span class="str">'a'</span>, <span class="str">'b'</span>, <span class="str">'c'</span>])     <span class="cm"># 'a,b,c'</span>
<span class="str">''</span>.<span class="fn">join</span>([<span class="str">'a'</span>, <span class="str">'b'</span>, <span class="str">'c'</span>])      <span class="cm"># 'abc'  — empty string glues them directly together</span></div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          split() is like cutting a necklace — you pick where to cut (the delimiter) and end up with separate beads (list elements). join() is stringing them back together — you choose the thread (the separator string) that goes between each bead.
        </div>

        <div class="trap">
          <span class="trap-label">⚠️ join() SYNTAX IS BACKWARDS FROM WHAT YOU'D EXPECT</span>
          It's <kbd>"separator".join(list)</kbd> — not <kbd>list.join("separator")</kbd>. The separator calls join; the list is the argument. Almost everyone writes it backwards the first time.
        </div>

        <p><strong>Function vs. method — what's the difference?</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Function</strong> — stands alone, called directly: <kbd>len()</kbd>, <kbd>int()</kbd></li>
          <li><strong>Method</strong> — belongs to an object, called with dot notation: <kbd>s.split()</kbd>, <kbd>a.append()</kbd></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

