  <!-- ==================== LESSON 12 ==================== -->
  <div class="lesson" id="l12">
    <div class="lesson-header" onclick="toggleLesson('l12')">
      <span class="lesson-num">LESSON 12 · Week 8</span>
      <span class="lesson-title">Object Identity, Shallow/Deep Copy, Mutable vs Immutable</span>
      <span class="lesson-meta">3 core concepts</span>
      <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
    </div>
    <div class="lesson-body">

      <div class="framework-banner">
        <div class="framework-icon">🧬</div>
        <div>
          <h3>WHY THIS LESSON EXISTS</h3>
          <p>This is Python's "under the hood" lesson. Understanding the difference between references and copies prevents a class of extremely sneaky bugs — where you think you changed a copy, but you actually changed the original, and your data corrupts itself silently. This topic comes up constantly in assignments and interviews.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- IDENTITY -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-identity">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Object identity — <kbd>is</kbd> vs <kbd>==</kbd>
          <span class="tag tag-logic">🧠 Understand the logic</span>
        </div>

        <p>Every object in Python has a unique memory address, readable via <kbd>id()</kbd>.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><kbd>==</kbd> — checks whether two variables hold <strong>equal values</strong></li>
          <li><kbd>is</kbd> — checks whether two variables point to <strong>the exact same object in memory</strong> (equivalent to <kbd>id(a) == id(b)</kbd>)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="code-block">
a = <span class="str">"hello"</span>
b = <span class="str">"hel"</span>
b += <span class="str">"lo"</span>
a == b    <span class="cm"># True  — same value</span>
a <span class="kw">is</span> b   <span class="cm"># False — different objects in memory</span>

<span class="cm"># b = a copies the reference, so they share the same object</span>
a = <span class="num">400</span>
b = a     <span class="cm"># b and a now point to the same object</span>
a <span class="kw">is</span> b   <span class="cm"># True</span>
b = <span class="num">200</span>  <span class="cm"># b now points to a new object</span>
a <span class="kw">is</span> b   <span class="cm"># False</span></div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          <kbd>==</kbd> checks whether two people have the same name. <kbd>is</kbd> checks whether they're literally the same person (same ID number). Two strangers can both be named "Alex" (== True) but still be two different people (is False).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SHALLOW VS DEEP COPY -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-copy">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Shallow copy vs. deep copy
          <span class="tag tag-logic">🧠 Understand the logic</span>
          <span class="tag tag-key">⭐ High-value exam topic</span>
        </div>

        <div class="importance-box">
          <span class="label">⚠️ THE MOST COMMON SOURCE OF SILENT BUGS</span>
          <kbd>list2 = list1</kbd> does NOT copy the list — it copies the reference. Both variables point to <strong>the same list</strong>. Change one, and the other changes too.
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
<span class="cm"># ❌ Looks like a copy — it isn't (both names point at the same list)</span>
list1 = [<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">2</span>, <span class="num">3</span>]
list2 = list1
list1[<span class="num">0</span>] = <span class="num">4</span>
<span class="fn">print</span>(list2)    <span class="cm"># [4, 2, 3]  — list2 changed too!</span>

<span class="cm"># ✅ Actual copy (works for 1D lists)</span>
list3 = [<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">2</span>, <span class="num">3</span>]
list4 = list3.<span class="fn">copy</span>()    <span class="cm"># option 1</span>
list4 = list3[:]          <span class="cm"># option 2 — same effect</span>
list3[<span class="num">0</span>] = <span class="num">4</span>
<span class="fn">print</span>(list4)    <span class="cm"># [1, 2, 3]  — unaffected!</span>

<span class="cm"># ⚠️ Nested lists need copy.deepcopy()</span>
<span class="kw">import</span> copy
nested = [[<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">2</span>], [<span class="num">3</span>, <span class="num">4</span>]]
real_copy = copy.<span class="fn">deepcopy</span>(nested)    <span class="cm"># every level is now fully independent</span></div>

        <div class="analogy">
          <span class="analogy-label">💡 REAL-LIFE ANALOGY</span>
          <strong>Alias (list2 = list1)</strong> — you give your friend a key to your apartment. You live in the same place. If she moves your couch, it's gone when you get home.<br><br>
          <strong>Deep copy</strong> — you build your friend an identical apartment next door. Whatever she does to hers, yours is completely untouched.
        </div>

        <table class="compare-table">
          <tr><th>Situation</th><th>How to get a true independent copy</th></tr>
          <tr><td>1D list (flat)</td><td><kbd>.copy()</kbd> or <kbd>[:]</kbd> — either works</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Nested list</td><td>Must use <kbd>copy.deepcopy()</kbd> — otherwise the inner lists are still shared</td></tr>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- MUTABLE IMMUTABLE -->
      <div class="topic" id="anchor-mutable">
        <div class="topic-title">
          Mutable vs Immutable
          <span class="tag tag-memory">📝 Memorize the categories</span>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-grid">
          <div class="concept-card" style="border-color:#7dd4b0">
            <strong>✅ Mutable (changeable)</strong>
            <span>list, dict<br>Can be modified in place — the object's id stays the same</span>
          </div>
          <div class="concept-card" style="border-color:#e98585">
            <strong>❌ Immutable (fixed)</strong>
            <span>str, int, float, bool<br>"Changing" creates a new object — the id changes</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
<span class="cm"># String — immutable, cannot be modified in place</span>
t = <span class="str">"hello"</span>
t[<span class="num">0</span>] = <span class="str">"1"</span>    <span class="cm"># ❌ TypeError — strings don't support item assignment</span>

<span class="cm"># List — mutable, modify freely</span>
lst = [<span class="num">1</span>, <span class="num">2</span>, <span class="num">3</span>]
lst[<span class="num">0</span>] = <span class="num">99</span>    <span class="cm"># ✅ No problem at all</span></div>

        <p style="margin-top:0.75rem">One important consequence: when you pass a list to a function, the function receives the <strong>reference</strong>. If it modifies the list, <strong>the original outside the function changes too</strong>. This is not true for ints or strings — keep it in mind to avoid surprises.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

